full diff: https://github.com/containerd/containerd/compare/v1.4.3...v1.4.4

Release notes:

The fourth patch release for `containerd` 1.4 contains a fix for CVE-2021-21334
along with various other minor issues.
See [GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4](https://github.com/containerd/containerd/security/advisories/GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4)
for more details related to CVE-2021-21334.

Notable Updates

- Fix container create in CRI to prevent possible environment variable leak between containers
- Update shim server to return grpc NotFound error
- Add bounds on max `oom_score_adj` value for shim's AdjustOOMScore
- Update task manager to use fresh context when calling shim shutdown
- Update Docker resolver to avoid possible concurrent map access panic
- Update shim's log file open flags to avoid containerd hang on syscall open
- Fix incorrect usage calculation

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

full diff: https://github.com/containerd/containerd/compare/v1.4.3...v1.4.4

Release notes:

The fourth patch release for `containerd` 1.4 contains a fix for CVE-2021-21334
along with various other minor issues.
See [GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4](https://github.com/containerd/containerd/security/advisories/GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4)
for more details related to CVE-2021-21334.

Notable Updates

- Fix container create in CRI to prevent possible environment variable leak between containers
- Update shim server to return grpc NotFound error
- Add bounds on max `oom_score_adj` value for shim's AdjustOOMScore
- Update task manager to use fresh context when calling shim shutdown
- Update Docker resolver to avoid possible concurrent map access panic
- Update shim's log file open flags to avoid containerd hang on syscall open
- Fix incorrect usage calculation

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

Change-Id: I4c879184f93dc89405659bd0a4ea5acd1332f614","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/d48d6758481ee0e24bd60996daceb241d272d310"},{"sha":"0359bf560ced5940b6504120a28ea980d1691ad8","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference: Provider finer granule control over kSelect.

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

- Update task manager to use fresh context when calling shim shutdown
- Update Docker resolver to avoid possible concurrent map access panic

- Fix incorrect usage calculation

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358292147
Change-Id: I3c4aa367d09e6fbe4543e66121371a4a4e6d311f","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ddavis-2015/tensorflow/commits/50ea65ffdab19e4ffaf90b3b762bb5756b5e5809"},{"sha":"c29e9f25e761df06e1d401868fbc0ff2071a0ed2","author":{"name":"Daniel Ellis","email":"debc5fc5255503ceceb6184687cd26898e40e8ac@google.com"},"message":"Handle garbage collection race condition.

An exception is being thrown when objects that use `CapturableResourceDeleter` are garbage collected at the end of a program's life.  This can happen in very normal circumstances, such as when using `saved_model_cli` to inspect a model.

The cause of the exception appears to be a race condition with garbage collection between `CapturableResourceDeleter` and `ScopedTFFunction`. Both define a custom finalizer (`__del__`); `CaptureableResourceDeleter`'s finalizer ultimately calls a concrete function which calls an `_EagerDefinedFunction` which attempts to load and execute a `ScopedTFFunction`.

In the case of multiple objects in a reference cycle all going unreachable during the same garbage collection cycle, we get no guaranteed ordering for which of the objects will be collected first. In the case of the exception, `ScopedTFFunction` is collected first and its underlying function is deleted. Later, `CapturableResourceDeleter` is called, which fails, since the function it's trying to call is gone.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358313521
Change-Id: I9100dbf8d82dc695a896a7b61c433ef38865ec9d","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ddavis-2015/tensorflow/commits/61f4be7e5b5a0a7b87c60107a6785c40d21cbab1"},{"sha":"051542c14d85ce8de8bae5822fa746d335ce3df6","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"Switch tensorflow::Subprocess to use posix_spawnp() instead of fork()/execvp() on non-Android POSIX platforms.

The goal of this change is to avoid calling pthread_atfork() handlers. Some libraries, in particular the version of OpenBLAS included in NumPy, have buggy pthread_atfork() handlers. See https://github.com/xianyi/OpenBLAS/pull/3111 and https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5713 for details.

Now, while we can and have fixed the buggy atfork handlers, it will take some time for the fix to be deployed in a NumPy release and for users to update to a new NumPy release. So we also take an additional step: avoid running atfork handlers in Subprocess.

My copy of the glibc documentation says:
"
According  to  POSIX, it unspecified whether fork handlers established with pthread_atfork(3)
are called when posix_spawn() is invoked.  On glibc, fork handlers are  called  only  if  the
child is created using fork(2).
"
It appears glibc 2.24 and newer do not call pthread_atfork() handlers from posix_spawn().

Using posix_spawn() should be at least no worse than an explicit fork()/execvp() pair, and on glibc it should do the right thing.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361656725
Change-Id: I4c879184f93dc89405659bd0a4ea5acd1332f614","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/d48d6758481ee0e24bd60996daceb241d272d310"},{"sha":"0359bf560ced5940b6504120a28ea980d1691ad8","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference: Provider finer granule control over kSelect.

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

Change-Id: I4c879184f93dc89405659bd0a4ea5acd1332f614","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/d48d6758481ee0e24bd60996daceb241d272d310"},{"sha":"0359bf560ced5940b6504120a28ea980d1691ad8","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference: Provider finer granule control over kSelect.

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

Release notes:

The fourth patch release for `containerd` 1.4 contains a fix for CVE-2021-21334
along with various other minor issues.
See [GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4](https://github.com/containerd/containerd/security/advisories/GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4)
for more details related to CVE-2021-21334.

Notable Updates

- Fix container create in CRI to prevent possible environment variable leak between containers
- Update shim server to return grpc NotFound error
- Add bounds on max `oom_score_adj` value for shim's AdjustOOMScore
- Update task manager to use fresh context when calling shim shutdown
- Update Docker resolver to avoid possible concurrent map access panic
- Update shim's log file open flags to avoid containerd hang on syscall open
- Fix incorrect usage calculation

Change-Id: I4c879184f93dc89405659bd0a4ea5acd1332f614","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/d48d6758481ee0e24bd60996daceb241d272d310"},{"sha":"0359bf560ced5940b6504120a28ea980d1691ad8","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference: Provider finer granule control over kSelect.

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361667493
Change-Id: Ia01987df6c53f7fad8dd12b9702f526c57f9f831","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/2e142ab79734c51d429869029169853f742d9684"},{"sha":"1c677615d027fe87267f412b7dacf6b6b09cc231","author":{"name":"Berkin Ilbeyi","email":"5f773b6479653d0f1ae8fe9abb2a70525c143dd2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Add support for async ops to get allocations in the alternate memory space

Async ops such as collective-permute-start/collective-permute-done need a stable
allocation until the async op completes. This CL adds support for these ops to
get alternate memory allocations for their source and destination buffers.

Also, when picking an offset for a buffer in the memory space assignment pass,
we now look and try to find an offset that is available for uses that belong to
different AllocationValues (but can be assigned the same buffer). For example,
if a value is used by an HLO while loop, this enables us to search for an offset
for the buffer that is alive for the uses after the while loop (since each
HloPosition, such as a while HLO instruction, forces the creation of a new
AllocationValue).

Change-Id: I4c879184f93dc89405659bd0a4ea5acd1332f614","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/d48d6758481ee0e24bd60996daceb241d272d310"},{"sha":"0359bf560ced5940b6504120a28ea980d1691ad8","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference: Provider finer granule control over kSelect.

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361667493
Change-Id: Ia01987df6c53f7fad8dd12b9702f526c57f9f831","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/2e142ab79734c51d429869029169853f742d9684"},{"sha":"1c677615d027fe87267f412b7dacf6b6b09cc231","author":{"name":"Berkin Ilbeyi","email":"5f773b6479653d0f1ae8fe9abb2a70525c143dd2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Add support for async ops to get allocations in the alternate memory space

Async ops such as collective-permute-start/collective-permute-done need a stable
allocation until the async op completes. This CL adds support for these ops to
get alternate memory allocations for their source and destination buffers.

Also, when picking an offset for a buffer in the memory space assignment pass,
we now look and try to find an offset that is available for uses that belong to
different AllocationValues (but can be assigned the same buffer). For example,
if a value is used by an HLO while loop, this enables us to search for an offset
for the buffer that is alive for the uses after the while loop (since each
HloPosition, such as a while HLO instruction, forces the creation of a new
AllocationValue).

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

Change-Id: Ia01987df6c53f7fad8dd12b9702f526c57f9f831","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/2e142ab79734c51d429869029169853f742d9684"},{"sha":"1c677615d027fe87267f412b7dacf6b6b09cc231","author":{"name":"Berkin Ilbeyi","email":"5f773b6479653d0f1ae8fe9abb2a70525c143dd2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Add support for async ops to get allocations in the alternate memory space

Async ops such as collective-permute-start/collective-permute-done need a stable
allocation until the async op completes. This CL adds support for these ops to
get alternate memory allocations for their source and destination buffers.

Also, when picking an offset for a buffer in the memory space assignment pass,
we now look and try to find an offset that is available for uses that belong to
different AllocationValues (but can be assigned the same buffer). For example,
if a value is used by an HLO while loop, this enables us to search for an offset
for the buffer that is alive for the uses after the while loop (since each
HloPosition, such as a while HLO instruction, forces the creation of a new
AllocationValue).

Release notes:

The fourth patch release for `containerd` 1.4 contains a fix for CVE-2021-21334
along with various other minor issues.
See [GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4](https://github.com/containerd/containerd/security/advisories/GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4)
for more details related to CVE-2021-21334.

Notable Updates

- Fix container create in CRI to prevent possible environment variable leak between containers
- Update shim server to return grpc NotFound error
- Add bounds on max `oom_score_adj` value for shim's AdjustOOMScore
- Update task manager to use fresh context when calling shim shutdown
- Update Docker resolver to avoid possible concurrent map access panic
- Update shim's log file open flags to avoid containerd hang on syscall open
- Fix incorrect usage calculation

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

Change-Id: Ia01987df6c53f7fad8dd12b9702f526c57f9f831","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/2e142ab79734c51d429869029169853f742d9684"},{"sha":"1c677615d027fe87267f412b7dacf6b6b09cc231","author":{"name":"Berkin Ilbeyi","email":"5f773b6479653d0f1ae8fe9abb2a70525c143dd2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Add support for async ops to get allocations in the alternate memory space

Async ops such as collective-permute-start/collective-permute-done need a stable
allocation until the async op completes. This CL adds support for these ops to
get alternate memory allocations for their source and destination buffers.

Also, when picking an offset for a buffer in the memory space assignment pass,
we now look and try to find an offset that is available for uses that belong to
different AllocationValues (but can be assigned the same buffer). For example,
if a value is used by an HLO while loop, this enables us to search for an offset
for the buffer that is alive for the uses after the while loop (since each
HloPosition, such as a while HLO instruction, forces the creation of a new
AllocationValue).

Change-Id: I4c879184f93dc89405659bd0a4ea5acd1332f614","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/d48d6758481ee0e24bd60996daceb241d272d310"},{"sha":"0359bf560ced5940b6504120a28ea980d1691ad8","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference: Provider finer granule control over kSelect.

Previously if ANY value in the selector of kSelect is dynamic, we over-conservatively assume all resutls are dynamic.

This CL makes this logic smarter by providing better inspection over the selector values:
- An optional constant literal slice class, which allows us to ask two questions at the same time:
   1. Is the value constant or dynamic? If it's dynamic, an absl::nullopt is returned.
   2. What's the constant value: If the value is constant, a concrete value is returned.
- Use the new optional constant literal slice class in evaluating kSelect:
  - If a value in the selector is dynamic, corresponding result is dynamic.
  - If a value in the selector is constant, evaluate it and use it as the selector to select either the true branch of false branch.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361667493
Change-Id: Ia01987df6c53f7fad8dd12b9702f526c57f9f831","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/2e142ab79734c51d429869029169853f742d9684"},{"sha":"1c677615d027fe87267f412b7dacf6b6b09cc231","author":{"name":"Berkin Ilbeyi","email":"5f773b6479653d0f1ae8fe9abb2a70525c143dd2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Add support for async ops to get allocations in the alternate memory space

Async ops such as collective-permute-start/collective-permute-done need a stable
allocation until the async op completes. This CL adds support for these ops to
get alternate memory allocations for their source and destination buffers.

Also, when picking an offset for a buffer in the memory space assignment pass,
we now look and try to find an offset that is available for uses that belong to
different AllocationValues (but can be assigned the same buffer). For example,
if a value is used by an HLO while loop, this enables us to search for an offset
for the buffer that is alive for the uses after the while loop (since each
HloPosition, such as a while HLO instruction, forces the creation of a new
AllocationValue).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

Release notes:

The fourth patch release for `containerd` 1.4 contains a fix for CVE-2021-21334
along with various other minor issues.
See [GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4](https://github.com/containerd/containerd/security/advisories/GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4)
for more details related to CVE-2021-21334.

Notable Updates

- Fix container create in CRI to prevent possible environment variable leak between containers
- Update shim server to return grpc NotFound error
- Add bounds on max `oom_score_adj` value for shim's AdjustOOMScore
- Update task manager to use fresh context when calling shim shutdown
- Update Docker resolver to avoid possible concurrent map access panic
- Update shim's log file open flags to avoid containerd hang on syscall open
- Fix incorrect usage calculation

[{"sha":"bd45095b9c1b79f36f66053f17a92d71cc66984b","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"exprstress: A randomized stress tester for expression evaluation

Although we have a fair number of hand-written unit tests for different
permutations of expression evaluation, when writing those we tend to
favor relatively straightforward situations which only include a single
operator or function at a time, and thus we can sometimes miss including
test cases for less common situations that can arise when combining
different features together.

This new package and its associated CLI tool are intended to randomly
generate various valid expressions with different combinations of
expression operators and functions from the Terraform language, and then
check to make sure that they evaluate successfully and produce a result
of the expected type, mode, and sensitivity. Hopefully this will allow us
to find problems that we wouldn't think to test.

This is a similar sort of idea as fuzz testing, but at a higher level of
abstraction where the input is intended to always be a valid expression
and we're focused on the evaluator, rather than generating random bytes
and trying to crash the HCL parser. This is a form of property-based
testing, albeit applying the same set of properties to all possible
expressions rather than testing unique properties of each expression type.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/bd45095b9c1b79f36f66053f17a92d71cc66984b"}]

Change-Id: Ia01987df6c53f7fad8dd12b9702f526c57f9f831","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/2e142ab79734c51d429869029169853f742d9684"},{"sha":"1c677615d027fe87267f412b7dacf6b6b09cc231","author":{"name":"Berkin Ilbeyi","email":"5f773b6479653d0f1ae8fe9abb2a70525c143dd2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Add support for async ops to get allocations in the alternate memory space

Async ops such as collective-permute-start/collective-permute-done need a stable
allocation until the async op completes. This CL adds support for these ops to
get alternate memory allocations for their source and destination buffers.

Also, when picking an offset for a buffer in the memory space assignment pass,
we now look and try to find an offset that is available for uses that belong to
different AllocationValues (but can be assigned the same buffer). For example,
if a value is used by an HLO while loop, this enables us to search for an offset
for the buffer that is alive for the uses after the while loop (since each
HloPosition, such as a while HLO instruction, forces the creation of a new
AllocationValue).

full diff: https://github.com/containerd/containerd/compare/v1.4.3...v1.4.4

Release notes:

The fourth patch release for `containerd` 1.4 contains a fix for CVE-2021-21334
along with various other minor issues.
See [GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4](https://github.com/containerd/containerd/security/advisories/GHSA-36xw-fx78-c5r4)
for more details related to CVE-2021-21334.

Notable Updates

- Fix container create in CRI to prevent possible environment variable leak between containers
- Update shim server to return grpc NotFound error
- Add bounds on max `oom_score_adj` value for shim's AdjustOOMScore
- Update task manager to use fresh context when calling shim shutdown
- Update Docker resolver to avoid possible concurrent map access panic
- Update shim's log file open flags to avoid containerd hang on syscall open
- Fix incorrect usage calculation
